title: Spam in Icelandic?
author: christian
content: "<p>Hmm, found this in my mailbox today:</p> \t<blockquote> \t<p>Og einn dag . .inginu er menn gengu fj.lmennir til L.gbergs og er .ar var lykt a. m.la l.gskilum .. kvaddi Gunnlaugur s.r hlj..s og m.lti: &#8220;Er Hrafn h.r .nundarson?&#8221;</p> \t</blockquote> \t<p>Accompanied by the picture of a certain female I&#8217;ve never met, a text of a sexual nature and a web address.</p> \t<p>But that last part wasn&#8217;t even the most interesting, it was the text. It obviously is no English; but by a coincidence I could clearly recognize it as being written in the language of the Icelanders.</p> \t<p>A little searching revealed that we&#8217;re dealing here with an extract from <a href=\"http://www.skolavefur.is/_opid/islenska/bokmenntir/isl_sogur/tegund/sagas/sogur/gunnlaugssaga/kaflar/11/index.htm\">chapter 11</a> of <a href=\"http://www.skolavefur.is/_opid/islenska/bokmenntir/isl_sogur/tegund/sagas/sogur/gunnlaugssaga/\">Gunnlaugs saga</a>:</p> \t<blockquote> \t<p>Og einn dag &aacute; &thorn;inginu er menn gengu fj&ouml;lmennir til L&ouml;gbergs og er &thorn;ar var lykt a&eth; m&aelig;la l&ouml;gskilum &thorn;&aacute; kvaddi Gunnlaugur s&eacute;r hlj&oacute;&eth;s og m&aelig;lti: &#8220;Er Hrafn h&eacute;r &Ouml;nundarson?&#8221;</p> \t</blockquote> \t<blockquote> \t<p>And on one day of the <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thing_%28assembly%29\">thing</a> (an assembly) many people gathered to the <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/L%D6gberg\">L&ouml;gberg</a> (the hill on <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thingvellir\">&THORN;ingvellir</a> where law was spoken) and there was a smell of talk about the definition of a law when Gunnlaugur took the floor and spoke &#8220;Is Hrafn here &Ouml;nundur&#8217;s son?&#8221;</p> \t</blockquote> \t<p>J&aelig;ja&#8230; Well, I haven&#8217;t read the saga yet, but now I might, thanks to some spam on a rainy day :)</p> \t<p>Detail for the Lord of the Rings fans; Gunnlaugs nickname is <em>Ormstunga</em>; Worm-Tongue or Snake-Tongue. Guess where J.R.R. got Gr&iacute;ma&#8217;s name!</p>"
